FT  26 JUL 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The 25th anniversary of man on the moon has enabled the historians to take a
more considered view of what now seems like ancient history. In Network
First (ITV at 10.40) James Burke examines Apollo 13, the craft that nearly
floundered in space when an electrical fault left the crew with just
fourteen minutes of oxygen. They were forced to cram into their Lunar
Excursion Module, but as the world held its breath they returned safely,
just, and now tell their uncensored tale.
Rugby has always been a national totem among whites in South Africa. A Whole
Different Ball Game looks at how will it fare in a multi-racial democracy.
Already 'development clinics' are turning out skilled black players who seem
certain to become the Springboks of the future. (BBC 2 7.40).
No one has stirred up psychology in the UK more than Hans Eysenck whose
controversial views on such matters as inherited intelligence and the
spuriousness of psychiatry have raised hackles in his profession. That some
of his ideas come with impressive data makes him even more of a Heretic (BBC
2 10.00).
</TEXT>
