<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JUL 94 / Minister welcomes building review
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government yesterday welcomed proposals to reduce construction costs by
stemming contract abuses and improving services - but would not commit
itself to promoting new legislation.
Viscount Ullswater, appointed construction minister in last week's
reshuffle, said: 'The government is willing in principle to consider
legislation if the need for it is adequately demonstrated.'
It was the government's first opportunity to respond to an independent
review of the construction industry which called for a construction
contracts bill to improve payment and dispute procedures.
The review, sponsored by the industry and the government, said that it
should be mandatory to appoint independent adjudicators to resolve
conflicts, reducing the need for costly legislation.
A bill would permit trust funds to be established to hold contract cash to
protect companies should customers or contractors fail. Sub-contractors
would be able to charge punitive interest for late payments.
Viscount Ullswater said yesterday that the government welcomed the overall
thrust of the review. As a first step the Department of the Environment
would support the creation of an implementation forum, representing the
industry and its leading customers, 'to oversee the follow-up work necessary
to take forward the report'.
Sir Michael Latham, the former Conservative MP and ex-director of the
Housebuilders Federation who led the investigation into the industry, would
become chairman of the implementation forum.
Viscount Ullswater said this would advise whether a more permanent
administrative machinery was required to pursue the proposals and cut
construction costs by up to 30 per cent.
</TEXT>
