<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JUL 94 / Watchdog discovers defects in fair ride
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Investigators from the safety watchdog said yesterday they had found
'deficiencies' in the world's tallest rollercoaster after a crash that
injured 26 people.
The 235 ft ride at Blackpool, Lancashire - the 'Pepsi Max Big One' - was
officially opened a week before the accident earlier this month. It will
remain closed under a Health and Safety Executive prohibition notice issued
last Friday while investigations continue. The watchdog said the notice was
served on Blackpool Pleasure Beach, the operator, 'requiring it to address
deficiencies in the ride's braking and control systems'.
The accident happened when a train travelling at 35mph was not halted by a
computer-controlled brake and ploughed into the back of another.
Pleasure Beach said its staff would test the ride now that the watchdog had
returned it to the company's control.
'We are now allowed to start implementing their recommendations. We are
still no nearer a conclusion regarding the computer,' it said.
Arrow Dynamics, the US maker of the ride, is still examining the computer
systems that should have made it impossible for two trains to collide.
</TEXT>
