<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JUL 94 / High hurdles are the norm for investment: Gillian Tett on
the rates of return being used to assess new projects
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
As Mr Eddie George, governor of the Bank of England, presses on with his
campaign to persuade UK companies to lower target rates of return from
investments, a company such as Whitbread might give him cause to wince.
In spite of Mr George's warnings that high targets could stifle investment
and undermine the economic recovery, the company has little intention of
lowering its targets. Mr David Reed, director of corporate communications at
Whitbread, said: 'If anything our rates of return will rise this year.' The
most likely shift would be from a five-year pay-back to four years.
Comments such as these may not surprise the City, in light of the
Confederation of British Industry's survey earlier this week which showed
most companies keeping high investment hurdles - minimum targets for rates
of return - and inflation assumptions above government targets.
What may give economists more food for thought is that many companies reject
warnings that high hurdles might be hampering investment - not least because
inflation expectations matter less than uncertainty about demand.
Mr Reed pointed out that Whitbread's move to higher hurdles went hand in
hand with a new investment programme. He said: 'High hurdles are not a bar
to investment. We will raise our rate of capital investment by 50 per cent
this year.'
The example reflects a message about investment complexity that is being
echoed by most companies, as the Confederation of British Industry prepares
to publish its latest quarterly survey indicating manufacturing investment
intentions today.
Sir David Lees, chairman of the industrial group GKN, said it operated a
hurdle rate of about 20 per cent - a benchmark that had been maintained
through recent years, although it rose slightly in the late 1980s. He
insisted, however, that this varied from project to project, and said that
hurdle rates remained only one factor in his assessment of business
decisions.
He said: 'We have not formally changed our benchmark, although we would be
more easily persuaded in marginal cases by the somewhat better outlook for
inflation.' It was likely to take two more years of low inflation to
convince most businesses to change their inflation expectations.
Mr Derek Bonham, chief executive of the Anglo-American conglomerate Hanson,
is a little more upbeat. Mr Bonham said that last year Hanson lowered its
target rate of return 'in light of a changed inflation and interest-rate
environment. We use a mixture of methods but in the broadest sense you could
say we moved it from a four-year pay-back period to a a five-year one'.
Mr David Newlands, finance director of the defence and electronics group
GEC, has indicated that he expects little change to his company's hurdle
rates. However, he said: 'The rate of return that we look for depends on the
risk involved in the project. For some high-technology areas you would
expect a high rate of return - it's much more complex than surveys might
suggest.'
</TEXT>
