<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JUL 94 / High-tech groups plan 49% staff growth
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM, Wales and West Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A survey of more than 200 high-technology companies in England has found
that they expect staff numbers to grow by an average of 49 per cent in the
next five years.
The survey, by Touche Ross, the accountancy firm, covered organisations in
four regions - the north-west, Cambridge, the south coast and the west of
England - and sought to find reasons for their selection of location. In
spite of the predicted growth in their size, most companies expected to
remain in their existing region.
Companies listed the availability of a well-trained workforce and good
communications as the most important factors in influencing prosperity.
Quality of life, low staff costs and the proximity of an international
airport were regarded as the next most important points.
The research was carried out for the Western Development Partnership, a
regeneration agency, as part of a report published yesterday on
high-technology industry in Avon and its neighbouring counties of Wiltshire,
Gloucestershire and Somerset.
Survey respondents in these counties regarded the west as a poorer location
than the other areas. Companies elsewhere gave the region an even lower
rating.
The report says: 'This may be due to ignorance of the west of England, a
lack of a regional identity and uncertainty as to the precise area being
delineated - especially perhaps confusion with the more remote counties of
Devon and Cornwall.'
The report said the west had failed to build a strong position in high
technology 'although it had three strong universities, other centres of
excellence and a nucleus of high-tech businesses'.
High Technology in and around Avon. Western Development Partnership, 100
Victoria Street, Bristol BS1 6HZ. Pounds 15.
</TEXT>
