<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JUL 94 / Ruling boosts compensation prospects for Names
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The prospects of Lloyd's Names winning further compensation for losses
suffered in the insurance market in the 1980s were yesterday enhanced after
the House of Lords ruled that claims could be brought under the law of tort.
Five law lords ruled that Names could bring actions under tort law, which
allows for damages claims not related to alleged breaches of contract.
The ruling clears the way for Names to bring more actions seeking
compensation, since under tort law claims can be made up to 12 years from
the date when the alleged damage was discovered. Claims for breach of
contract have to be started within six years of the action complained of.
Mr Michael Deeny, chairman of the Gooda Walker Action Group, said it would
start proceedings against Littlejohn Frazer, the former Gooda Walker
auditors. The action to claim more than Pounds 100m compensation would
centre on the use of 'time and distance' policies by Gooda Walker's
syndicate 290, he said.
The House of Lords also upheld a Court of Appeal ruling that members' agents
were liable for the negligence of managing agents - a decision which
confirms the ability of Names to claim compensation from the 'error and
omission' insurance policies held by the members' agents. The E&amp;O cover
arranged by the members' agents totals about Pounds 1.1bn.
The Gooda Walker High Court case resumed yesterday with the start of closing
submissions. Mr Geoffrey Vos QC, for more than 3,000 Gooda Walker Names who
are suing the agency for more than Pounds 600m, said the agency's
underwriters had 'thrown away the rule book' and carried out their work in
an ad hoc, almost reckless manner.
During the hearing the judge, Mr Justice Phillips, said he had 'a lot of
sympathy' with the views on excess loss insurance expressed by Mr Ulrich von
Eicken, a former Munich Re executive who appeared as an expert witness for
the Names.
Mr Von Eicken had said that writing excess loss on excess loss business  - a
practice carried out by Gooda Walker - was an aberration since it could not
be properly rated.
Submissions will end this week. The judgment is expected in September.
</TEXT>
