<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JUL 94 / Monopoly panel rapped as 'toothless'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Competition policy has become reactive, slow and unpredictable and does
little to deter companies from abusing their market position, the Consumers'
Association says today.
Mr Stephen Locke, the association's director of policy, says in an article
published today in Consumer Policy Review that competition policy is in
urgent need of review.
Mr Locke says the Monopolies and Mergers Commission, which should be 'a
fearless guardian of the consumer interest, is gradually diminishing into a
toothless watchdog'.
He adds: 'From having one of the most effective and feared competition
regimes in the western world, the UK has slipped into the league of
also-rans, suspected by many of our international colleagues of being a soft
touch when it comes to abuses of market power and anti-competitive
agreements.'
The association calls for rules that are more clear, faster investigations,
more openness in decision-making and properly resourced watchdogs.
It also calls for compensation for consumers when companies over-price goods
or services or adopt restrictive practices. Customers who suffer loss should
be able to get damages, as in other countries.
There should be provision for class actions where consumer organisations
would be able to launch proceedings against companies abusing market power
on behalf of consumers generally.
The association says that recent reports by the monopolies commission on new
cars, perfume prices, ice cream, mortgage valuations and compact discs have
proved 'disastrous' for consumers.
Mr Locke says these reports have become 'progressively more corporatist in
tone and supportive of the status quo'.
The association says that competition law is too imprecise and therefore
unpredictable. Mr John Beishon, chief executive of the Consumers'
Association, has told association staff that he will consider withdrawing
recognition from two unions and sacking members who strike unless a pay
dispute is called off by August 1.
</TEXT>
<XX>
