<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JUL 94 / Unions offer Blair a deal on party link
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Unions have offered a deal to Mr Tony Blair, the new Labour leader, which
would give him substantial freedom in policy-making in return for an
agreement not to challenge further their constitutional position in the
party.
Many union leaders were taken aback by Mr Blair's statement last Friday that
the unions would have no privileged place in the party.
One union official said: 'Privately we were disappointed that the union
issue was raised so quickly, but we decided not to react.'
Union leaders, symbolically pushed to the back of the hall at Mr Blair's
victory rally, know that they are not held in high esteem by the Blair camp,
which believes they run increasingly unrepresentative bodies.
But they have no strategy to challenge the Labour leader with motions on
specific levels for a minimum wage or targets for reducing unemployment at
this year's Trades Union Congress or Labour conferences.
They do, however, believe that they can prevent Mr Blair re-opening the
issue of their presence in the party after the defeat they suffered last
year over one member, one vote.
The settlement that the principal union power brokers are seeking is spelt
out by Mr Tom Burlison, deputy general secretary of the GMB general union,
in the latest issue of the New Statesman.
He writes: 'Blair needs to consolidate the party constitution, while being
radical in policy and presentation.
'If his programme of radical reform were to include the party constitution
it would be a disaster.
'Those in the party who are embarrassed by the link have learnt to live with
it, and the unions in turn have learned that their role in the party has to
be legitimate. To upset that settlement would be suicide.'
The Blair camp can probably accept a standstill on the formal union position
in the party, which still includes a majority of the votes at party
conference, a substantial presence on the national executive committee, and
one-third of the votes to elect the leader.
But union influence on policy is likely to diminish as think-tanks such as
the Institute of Public Policy Research become more influential.
One senior union official said: 'We are really being told by the Blair camp:
'If you've got something interesting to say, say it, but you no longer
represent the majority of workers so we will make up our minds about whether
to accept it or not'.'
</TEXT>
