FT  26 JUL 94 / Bombing death toll in Argentina reaches 96
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Rescue workers in Buenos Aires yesterday pulled 27 more bodies from the
wreckage of Argentina's main Jewish centre and said there were 11 more still
in the rubble, bringing the confirmed toll from last week's bombing to 96,
Reuter reports.
Jewish groups, which have collected lists of those missing after the blast,
say the final death toll may be around 100.
General Meir Livne, who heads an Israeli army rescue team, confirmed
theories of a car bomb driven by a suicide driver. 'The crater in the road
and the sidewalk, and the engine we found inside the building point to a car
bomb,' he said. 'We think it may have been activated by the driver.'
The blast was the second such attack against Jews in Buenos Aires in two
years, 30 people having been killed by a car bomb at the Israeli embassy in
1992.
Mr Uzi Baram, Israeli tourism minister, was to meet Argentine President
Carlos Menem yesterday to ask the government to do its utmost to catch the
bombers.
Mr Peter Tarnoff, US State Department under-secretary, also arrived in
Argentina for talks with Mr Menem, the US embassy said.
