<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JUL 94 / UN chief hints at Balkan troop pull-out
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD and BRUCE CLARK
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The United Nations should consider pulling out of former Yugoslavia, whether
or not the current peace proposals are accepted, Mr Boutros Boutros Ghali,
UN secretary-general, said yesterday .
In a letter to the Security Council, he said the United Nations forces were
not strong enough either to enforce a peace settlement, or to withstand the
consequences of an escalating war.
He suggested that if the international community acted on its threat to
punish the Serbs for intransigence - through air strikes or by supplying
arms to their enemies - the UN would become a target for Serb retaliation.
'Such (punitive) actions would deliberately impinge on the basic military
interest of one of the parties and would therefore be likely to be
militarily resisted,' Mr Boutros Ghali warned.
In Bosnia, Serb forces seemed already to be embarking on a war of nerves
with the UN. Yesterday, they challenged the UN to call in air strikes by
firing heavy weapons near the 'safe haven' of Gorazde for a second day.
The UN also blamed the Serbs for the anti-aircraft fire at Sarajevo airport
last week which has forced the suspension of relief flights. The Serbs have
denied responsibility.
In a third challenge to the UN, the Serbs refused to allow the evacuation of
35 sick people from Gorazde unless all Serb prisoners held by the Moslem-led
Bosnian government were released.
Negotiators from the five-nation contact group which has devised a partition
arrangement for Bosnia conferred in Moscow yesterday over how to react to
the Serbs' ambiguous reply to the proposal.
A statement by the group said they discussed 'additional measures aimed at
removing the objections from all sides in the conflict'.
The group's members - the US, Russia, Britain, France and Germany - were
united in pressing for acceptance of the peace deal but seemed split over
how to cope with its apparent failure. No firm decisions are expected until
the group's foreign ministers meet in Geneva at the weekend.
Mr Igor Ivanov, Russian first deputy foreign minister who chaired the
meeting, said before it began that they would continue to strive for
acceptance of the latest peace plan - accepted by the Croat-Moslem alliance
but in effect rejected by Bosnian Serb leaders.
'We believe we have a plan that is balanced and realistic and reflects the
interests of all sides,' Mr Ivanov said. 'It would hardly be expedient to
abandon it.'
General Pavel Grachev, the Russian defence minister, will arrive in former
Yugoslavia today, where he is expected to meet Serbia's President Slobodan
Milosevic and possibly the Bosnian Serbs as well.
Gen Grachev has often been in direct communication with General Ratko
Mladic, head of the Bosnian Serb army, and the Russian minister may be one
of the few people who can exercise any influence over the Serb commander.
Yesterday, Russia announced a wide-ranging defence co-operation agreement
with Greece calling for joint exercises, possible co-production of weapons
and the exchange of information on defence matters. Greece is the only
European Union member which shares Russia's traditional sympathy for the
Serbs.
</TEXT>
