<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JUL 94 / Company News (This Week): Kopper must walk critical
tightrope - Deutsche Bank
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Hilmar Kopper, Deutsche Bank's irascible chairman, will be choosing his
words carefully when he opens the German banking sector's half-year
reporting season at a press conference tomorrow. He has been advised that it
is time to start refurbishing Deutsche Bank's public image after the
calamities of the recent past, including the near collapse of
Metallgesellschaft and the Schneider property affair.
While more mishaps cannot be ruled out, and DM500m (Pounds 206.6m) has
already been set aside to cover Schneider losses, the bank's recent
statements that it expects 1994 provisioning for bad and doubtful debts to
fall from last year's DM3.3bn seem confident enough.
Operating profits after provisions were down 10 per cent after four months,
but there is increasing confidence among investors and analysts that some of
the ground will be made up by the end of the year.
The main reason is an expected drop in own-account earnings from last year's
bumper DM2bn. But improved commission income and better interest margins
should provide some compensation.
Deutsche's substantial stakes in corporations such as Daimler-Benz are seen
as having big recovery potential. Other attractions include hints that
Germany's biggest credit institution will celebrate its 125th birthday next
year with a handsome dividend bonus.
</TEXT>
