<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JUL 94 / Fewer companies at risk of collapse as recovery picks up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The financial health of British companies improved sharply in the second
quarter of this year as the economic recovery took hold, according to a
study published today.
The analysis of 360,000 UK companies contributing more than 75 per cent of
Britain's gross domestic product finds a marked reduction in the number
considered to be in a risky condition or in significant danger of
collapsing.
It is further confirmation that the recovery is gathering pace. Figures last
week showed that the GDP was 3.3 per cent higher in the second quarter than
in the same period of 1993 - the first time since 1989 that growth exceeded
3 per cent.
The analysis, published by the broker Barclays De Zoete Wedd using figures
from the Dun &amp; Bradstreet corporate database, shows that Pounds 6bn of bank
debt moved out of the high risk category during the first half of the year.
The upturn in credit quality was particularly marked in the south-east,
south-west and East Anglia. Property and transport companies improved most
strongly among industrial sectors, with manufacturing companies also
stabilising.
The study follows optimistic statements from the chairmen of Barclays and
National Westminster bank about improvements in bad debt provisions, and BZW
will today raise its forecast for banks' earnings this year by a total of
Pounds 385m.
The fall in the number of companies rated as significantly risky for banks
to lend to is the first marked improvement in credit quality noted since the
end of the recession, although quality has risen slowly since the end of
last year.
Mr Hugh Pye, banks analyst at BZW, said the figures showed a 'dramatic'
improvement in credit quality. He said the ratings emphasised cash flow, and
companies appeared to be benefiting from lower interest rates.
The improvement in credit quality could help banks to feel more confident
about lending money. Banks have reported only gradual increases in loan
volumes during the recovery, partly because of a perceived lack of
high-quality borrowers.
The report says the upturn in credit quality in the south-east is
significant, since the region contains 40 per cent of all UK companies by
number, as well as 49 per cent of all companies with a poor credit rating.
The regions with the best corporate credit quality are in the north of
England - with 13.5 per cent of companies in a poor condition. This compares
with 17.3 per cent in the UK as a whole.
Switch to foreign banks, Page 7
Samuel Brittan, Page 14
</TEXT>
