<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JUL 94 / Guide on pension payouts delayed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The final version of guidance on how to compensate investors who have
suffered from poor advice on personal pensions is unlikely to be available
until the autumn, about three months behind schedule.
The Securities and Investments Board, the City's chief watchdog, is expected
to announce this week its plans for pressing ahead with the guidelines for
life companies and independent financial advisers, while conceding that the
original timetable has slipped.
Public concern about the possible mis-selling of personal pensions to
customers transferring or opting out of occupational schemes erupted last
December.
Mr Andrew Large, SIB chairman, said then that all those affected would be
fully recompensed, and the government made clear that it expected effective
remedies to be introduced promptly.
The initial plan was for SIB to produce firm guidelines by the end of this
month. It is now expected to produce provisional guidelines next month, but
these could be revised 'at the edges' if there were difficulties with
implementation.
One of the problems causing the delay has been that the two studies
commissioned by SIB on the extent of poor advice given to customers - as
opposed to the extent of the failure to meet regulators' requirements - have
both fallen behind schedule.
Better information about the scale of compensation that may have to be paid
is needed before SIB can take a view on whether the provisional plans are
workable. A recent industry estimate put the total compensation bill at
between Pounds 400m and Pounds 800m.
</TEXT>
