<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JUL 94 / Transport 'to top pollution league'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES, Resources Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Transport will overtake power generation as the sector emitting the greatest
amount of carbon dioxide by the end of this decade. Yet demand for transport
fuel will slow if the government sticks to its target of raising road-fuel
duties by 5 per cent in real terms every year.
These are the main conclusions of a study of energy and the environment by
Cambridge Econometrics, the Cambridge-based consultancy.
The study found that while emissions from power generation will decline in
the years ahead, those from transport will continue to rise - particularly
from road transport which accounts for more than 90 per cent of all
transport emissions. But the rate of increase will slow.
The study challenges the traditional assumption that motorists readily
absorb higher petrol prices. It says new evidence suggests 'a much stronger
long-run response to price increases than previously estimated'. One reason
is that carmakers are now able to deliver greater efficiency benefits to
motorists who want to cut their petrol bills.
UK Energy and the Environment. Cambridge Econometrics, Covent Garden,
Cambridge CB1 2HS. By subscription.
</TEXT>
