<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JUL 94 / Public's economic optimism 'rising'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
    By LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Members of the public feel more optimistic about the state of the economy
and their employment prospects than at any time since May last year, says
the first of a series of surveys to be published monthly by the Financial
Times, Lisa Wood writes.
The index by MORI, the market research organisation, is based on two
surveys, one concerned with the fear of individuals in work becoming
redundant in the next 12 months, and the other on whether the public
generally expects the state of the economy to worsen.
The survey, entitled Mood of the Nation, was indexed at 100 in April 1993:
the higher the index, the more miserable the public. In its first month the
index was at 107. The misery level was highest last October (127) and at the
beginning of this year (124). In July the index was at 112, the lowest since
the index began.
There appear to be small but significant changes during the period in
individuals' financial behaviour, such as taking out loans or increasing
levels of credit card borrowing.
In 1993 26 per cent of the May sample said they intended to increase their
level of savings. That figure fell to 17 per cent this month. Fear of
redundancy itself had fallen slightly by this month, with 42 per cent of
respondents either 'very concerned' or 'fairly concerned' about losing their
jobs. In April, the last time the question was asked, the figure was 44 per
cent. Fear was highest last October, at 53 per cent. The survey was based on
interviews with 2,031 adults aged 18 plus at 150 constituencies across the
country with interviews conducted face to face between June 30 and July 4.
Copyright MORI/FT.
</TEXT>
