<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JUL 94 / Longer rail strikes 'will hit industry'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR and ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Producers of bulk materials normally carried by rail have warned of losses
and potentially serious shortages and delays for industry when the rail
strike is stepped up this week.
Signal workers are switching their action from 24-hour strikes to a 48-hour
stoppage from noon tomorrow to noon on Thursday, hitting train movements
over three days.
Supplies of crushed rock used for road construction and repairs in
south-east England will be particularly badly affected. The region, which
has no locally produced hard rock, imports about 250,000 tonnes a week by
rail.
ARC, a subsidiary of Hanson and one of the country's biggest aggregate
producers, said it could lose Pounds 1m a week when the rail strike worsens.
It said it was uneconomic to transport crushed rock by road for more than 80
miles to 100 miles.
ARC and Foster Yeoman, a large independent aggregate producer, jointly own
Mendip Rail, which transports 7m tonnes a year of West Country limestone to
more than 20 rail depots in south-east England - accounting for almost 60
per cent of crushed rock brought in to the region.
It said that running additional trains on non-strike days would not help,
and added: 'Few depots are large enough to accommodate stockpiles.'
British Steel, the third-largest railfreight customer, said that if 48-hour
strikes continued it would have to consider switching more freight to the
roads.
The concern of big customers was shared by the railfreight companies.
Railfreight Distribution, which handles containerised freight and Channel
tunnel freight business, warned that the escalation of the strike would hit
customer confidence.
Trainload Freight Southeast, one of three regional companies which together
carry about 90m tonnes a year of bulk materials, expressed concern about the
long-term effects of the strike.
So far it had been able to shift freight movements to non-strike days and
would be seeking to run more freight trains on strike days.
</TEXT>
