<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JUL 94 / Commanders defend privileges on the home front: Bruce Clark
weighs the arguments over providing luxury abodes for senior officers in the
armed forces
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRUCE CLARK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'When a civil servant who regards himself as comparable to me in seniority
and age sees me living in a nice house, it makes him jealous.' That is the
explanation offered by one senior commander for the recent controversy over
high living by top servicemen.
Distinguished officers in Her Majesty's forces require little encouragement
to hold forth about such matters as peace-keeping doctrine or the future of
submarine warfare.
But there is another subject which can arouse equally strong passions, but
is not so willingly discussed in front of outsiders: their own housing and
privileges.
This month's disclosure of a Pounds 387,000 refurbishment for the home of an
air chief marshal has reminded the public of one of the things that
distinguish service life from the civilian world - the glamour of life at
the top.
Many of the homes are listed houses. Among the finest is Admiralty House, a
Georgian mansion overlooking Plymouth Sound. Others are simply expanded
versions of the red-brick 'married quarters' on glorified housing estates
where most officers and their families live.
The commander of British forces in Hong Kong enjoys a lifestyle in the
colony's most fashionable district which would be the envy of many a
civilian millionaire. Until recently UK forces in Germany occupied some
splendid mansions commandeered in 1945.
There is no precise correlation between high living and responsibility. A
decade ago the senior general in Northern Ireland was obliged by security
factors to move from a mansion outside Belfast to more modest quarters
inside a barracks. And the flat in central London that goes with the job of
Chief of the Defence Staff is comfortable rather than opulent.
Officers' residences are, of course, 'tied cottages', like a bishop's palace
or an Oxford master's lodge. They go with particular jobs, and the service
couples who inhabit them are only too aware that in a year or two they will
be washing their own dishes in plainer surroundings.
Senior officers will have to fight a skilful rearguard action to hold on to
their privileges when defence costs are being trimmed and numbers reduced.
There are 67 official residences for senior officers in the UK, 26 for the
navy, 23 for the army and 18 for the Royal Air Force. Another 10 residences
are located abroad. However, 14 residences have been sold in the past year
and more disposals are expected.
These establishments will hardly make or break the defence budget. Over the
past two years the upkeep of senior officers' homes has cost the taxpayer
about Pounds 5m, covering everything from new roofs to routine maintenance.
A total of 278 domestic staff - 25 of them overseas - are employed in these
houses, at an annual cost to the taxpayer of about Pounds 5m.
Some of the most exotic homes to which an officer can aspire - as head of
the garrison in Brunei or military adviser in Oman - cost the UK taxpayer
nothing because they are paid for by local sultans.
When set against total annual defence spending of Pounds 23bn, the sums
spent on officers' homes seem paltry enough.
But looked at from another angle, the figures can be embarrassing. The
average staff costs for each senior officer come to about Pounds 65,000 a
year, while the average value of each official residence is about Pounds
500,000.
From the officers' point of view the trouble is that any case they advance
in support of this state of affairs can sound hollow and self-serving.
But there are some practical arguments in favour of the current
arrangements. Senior service jobs include a public-relations function which
is comparable to that of ambassadors.
Their homes have to double as conference centres, restaurants and hotels for
a stream of dignitaries ranging from parliamentary delegations to Middle
Eastern potentates shopping for weapons.
Jobs with responsibility for conflict zones such as Northern Ireland or
Bosnia keep the holder on duty for 24 hours a day. He needs to be in
frequent touch with operational headquarters and to live close to his place
of work.
Given that these positions are rotated every year or two, it makes better
sense to keep permanent official residences than to provide officers with
housing allowances and expect them to waste time searching for
accommodation.
But these bread-and-butter arguments are not the ones most officers would
use in defence of their homes.
In the end, they would say, a hint of mystique and glamour is one of the
intangibles that draws talented people to service careers - and spurs them
on to compete for posts whose salaries are modest by civilian standards.
Like so many aspects of service life, from drill to military tattoos, this
cannot easily be explained to accountants.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
