<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JUL 94 / Low turnout in Ukraine poll
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JILL BARSHAY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KIEV
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Repeat elections yesterday failed to fill the remaining quarter of Ukraine's
new parliament because of a low turnout. Preliminary results showed that
only 57 of the 112 districts surpassed the 50 per cent turnout threshold.
'It was a beautiful day. People were at their dachas concentrating on their
garden plots.' said Mr Yaropolk Kulchyckyj, Kiev head of the
Washington-based International Foundation for Electoral Systems. 'This is
the fifth time, they're tired of elections. Many people didn't even know
that elections were taking place.' Ukraine has been conducting a complete
democratic transfer of leadership from president down to councillors. The
result crushed hopes that democrats and moderates might be able to wrest
control of the 450-seat body from the Communists and their left-wing allies.
The empty seats are a result of Ukraine's inefficient electoral law, which
only managed to elect 338 deputies in two rounds of voting last March and
April. Further repeat elections for the invalid districts will need to be
rescheduled for later this year. In most of the 57 valid districts,
elections will still have to go to a second round run-off on August 7.
</TEXT>
