<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JUL 94 / Hutu refugees begin return journey to Rwanda: US army denies
claims that food drops were off-target
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LESLIE CRAWFORD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The tide of Rwandan Hutus seeking refuge in Zaire began to turn at the
weekend, with thousands heading home as cholera took hold in the camps along
the border, where up to 1,500 a day were estimated to be dying.
Three US military aircraft yesterday made the first drops in a planned
mission to bring food to refugees. A US army spokesman in Stuttgart said the
drops, north of the border town of Goma, had been successful and he denied
claims by aid workers that they had been off-target. Ms Alison Campbell, of
the aid organisation Care, said the operation was 'a waste of time and
resources of busy people in an emergency'.
The air drops followed a visit to Goma by Mr Kengo wa Dondo, Zaire's prime
minister, during which he reopened the frontier which had been closed since
Thursday. Refugees cheered and some crossed back into Rwanda.
Their return will be crucial to the new government installed last week in
the capital Kigali by the Tutsi-dominated Rwandan Patriotic Front, leaders
of which say their top priority is convincing the more than 2m Hutus who
have fled that their lives will not be under threat if they return.
Those who are dying in Goma from thirst, hunger, cholera or exhaustion fled
in fear of RPF reprisals for the genocide of the Tutsis conducted by the
former Hutu government.
'The international community must help us persuade refugees they will be
safe back home,' Rwanda's new prime minister, Mr Faustin Twagiramungu -
himself a Hutu - said. The former rebels of the RPF have taken pains to
appoint a mixed Hutu-Tutsi government to win the support of the majority
Hutu population. As well as the prime minister, his deputy, the president
and the justice minister are ethnic Hutus, and say they reject Rwanda's
ethnic divisions.
The new government promises to abolish the Rwandan identity card, which
identified the holder as belonging to the Hutu, Tutsi or pigmy Twa ethnic
group.
As part of the aid effort, Israel said yesterday it was airlifting a field
hospital, doctors and medical supplies to Goma.
However, the UN High Commissioner for Refugees and all relief agencies say
the only solution to the humanitarian catastrophe in Goma is the voluntary
repatriation of Hutu refugees. Mr Michel Moussalli, a special UNHCR envoy,
said: 'We need expatriates, non-government organisations, UN military
observers - the more the better.'
However, there were reports at the weekend of disappearances, blamed on RPF
forces in Kigali. Mrs Philomene Mukabarali, wife of former ambassador and
moderate Hutu politician Mr Silvestre Kamali, said yesterday her husband had
been abducted at an RPF road block in Kigali 10 days ago. The RPF denies
holding him.
Rwanda's new president, Page 3
</TEXT>
