<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUL 94 / International Company News: Kidder Peabody's Cerullo resigns
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Edward Cerullo, the head of fixed income at Kidder Peabody, yesterday
became the latest senior executive to resign from the troubled US securities
firm.
Kidder was rocked earlier this year by the discovery of what it claims was a
scheme to create fictitious profits of Dollars 350m by Mr Joseph Jett, a
bond trader in Mr Cerullo's division.
Both Kidder and Mr Cerullo depicted yesterday's resignation as a voluntary
act, not linked to a failure to supervise Mr Jett properly. In a statement,
Mr Cerullo said that he was leaving because, 'given the events of recent
months, I believe new management is best served by having its own team in
place'.
Asked whether it had asked for the resignation, Kidder said: 'This is an
independent decision by Ed Cerullo.' The resignation was 'solely due to the
reason stated' by Mr Cerullo, the company added.
The departure comes just days before the expected publication of an
investigation into the Jett allegations which is being carried out for
Kidder and its parent, General Electric, by Mr Gary Lynch, a former head of
enforcement at the Securities and Exchange Commission. GE indicated recently
that the report would be completed by early August.
The Lynch report, which has already taken longer to produce than initially
indicated, is expected to examine the adequacy of Kidder's controls in the
light of the allegations surrounding Mr Jett. Given his position as the
person directly responsible for supervising Mr Jett, questions had
inevitably been raised about Mr Cerullo's future at the firm, along with
that of Mr Richard O'Donnell, the company's chief financial officer, who
remains in place.
Kidder's chairman and chief executive, Mr Michael Carpenter, left the firm
at the end of last month, while Mr Michael Keehner, a former head of its
broking operations, resigned a week ago.
</TEXT>
